english:
  title: Memorial Requesting to Relinquish the Position of Counselor and Minister of Household Affairs
  author: Kim Bu-sik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    High office and grave responsibility await only the worthy—how can a weak and humble servant such as I presume to fill such a station? In my perplexity and shame, I know not what path to take.

    Your servant's lineage is obscure and humble, my nature dull and slow. Though I have devoted myself to learning, I cannot match the scholarship of Zixia; though I take up the brush to compose, I cannot enter the chamber of Sima Xiangru. By circumstance I have stumbled into official service, thereby soiling the seat of minister. My heart, though iron and stone in its resolve to serve the ruler with integrity, possesses only the narrow capacity of a measuring vessel—how can it encompass the vast designs of governing the realm? When one holds the axis and grasps the sphere of power, who would call it fitting? Better that I be cast into obscurity, for there it would be deemed proper.

    Yet suddenly, through undeserved favor, I have been elevated to participate in great affairs of state. When office rises high, responsibility grows heavy; when reputation exceeds measure, calumny multiplies. Having issued decrees in the outer court, I now face impeachment from the Censoriate. Rumor wears the mask of truth, and careless tongues make it seem inevitable; loose talk spawns fabrications, and detractors show no mercy. Though the Sage might distinguish right from wrong, public opinion dwells in suspicion and doubt.

    It is proper that I withdraw my inadequacy and yield to the worthy. How can I shamefully cling to honors unearned? I humbly beseech Your Majesty's boundless mercy and thunderbolt-swift resolve: adjust the lute and harp without forcing them out of tune; withdraw your commands as you would retract silken threads. When building a great mansion, one must select worthy timber for the frame; the worn-out horse, already exhausted, cannot bear the whip's sting. I pray you entrust this task to the able, that the wisdom of sages not be tarnished by my inadequacy.
  footnotes:
    - This is a formal memorial (표, pyo) of remonstrance in which Kim Bu-sik requests permission to resign from his prestigious appointment as Counselor-in-Chief and Minister of Household Affairs.
    - The references to Zixia (子夏), a disciple of Confucius, and Sima Xiangru (司馬相如), the renowned Han dynasty writer, are classical allusions to superior scholarship and literary skill that underscore the author's self-deprecating tone.
    - The 'Censoriate' (憲府, Heonbu) refers to the imperial censorate, the body responsible for impeaching and investigating officials—a common threat to ambitious ministers in traditional East Asian courts.
    - The imagery of 'tuning the lute' and 'retracting silken threads' are metaphors for correcting or reversing imperial edicts and appointments.
